[HealthMap/ProMED-mail map
Amazonas, Brazil: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5553455,3935

The bloody experience of these Brazilian children in Amazonas is, I'm afraid, not unusual in the interior of Amazonas as they sleep in hammocks and mosquito nets get dislodged. Vampire bats pose a significant risk also to cattle and horses.

The Milwaukee Protocol has gathered some controversy over the years and has not been consistently successful. To quote Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milwaukee_protocol): "Out of 36 rabies patients treated with the Milwaukee Protocol, 5 have survived. Giese's treatment regimen has undergone revision (the 2nd version omits the use of ribavirin). 2 of 25 patients treated under the 1st protocol survived. A further 10 patients have been treated under the revised protocol, with a further 2 survivors.

"In June 2011, another child survived infection with rabies without receiving the vaccine before showing symptoms. [PR], an 8-year-old girl from Willow Creek, California, contracted the disease in April 2011, but did not receive medical care until mid-May, after her grandmother took her to the doctor because of influenza-like symptoms that grew so serious, her grandmother said they resembled polio. The hospital said doctors followed the protocol established for Giese. [R] was placed in a drug-induced coma and received antiviral medications. She survived after spending 2 weeks in intensive care undergoing the treatments.

"Some critics say those survivors are due to the patients having a genetic rabies immunity and that the Milwaukee protocol has nothing to do with the survival rate; However this would imply the 5 patients all happened to coincidentally survive rabies while receiving the Milwaukee protocol -- despite no documented survivors before them.

"Ketamine has been shown to have a direct effect against the rabies virus."

But faced with certain death, it offers an opportunity. - Mod.MHJ]
